text: People are praising this for not being a more mainstream story, but it's not exactly original either; it's basically a "boy and his dog" with a _10,000 B.C._ setting.  The shots themselves are generally pretty, though the muted color palette I'm not a fan of.  Not exactly a fan of the actors either; nothing against them personally or even as actors (though the plain American accent works to the film's detriment, so I hope for the film's sake that the humans don't speak all that much) but they look too "white" to be portraying people of this time period.  The wildlife generally looks okay from an ecological point of view -- CGI isn't bad but it's clearly CGI; hopefully that gets improved between now and the release -- though the presence of an out-of-geological-place long-tailed sabertooth cat is a glaring flaw as someone familiar with paleontology and Ice Age megafauna.    Look like it'll be anywhere from "meh" to "alright" overall.  Probably something I'd rent after its release.

text: so it looks cool and all...but, what's with these Viking looking native Americans....I say Native Americans because those were clearly American Buffaloes (only found in N.A.). I understand it may not be a big deal to most people but I for one am getting tired of bs history... Of course every detail cannot be dug up and implemented but I feel the migration from the Asian continent is common knowledge and widely accepted as a reasonable explanation.  I don't feel the adherence to historical accuracy would take away from the movie...so I'm a bit baffled as to why it would be this blatantly stupid about it....then again, we have all these movies taking place in ancient Rome and Egypt with people taking on British accents so I guess things take time to change..anywho....just a thought.

text: If you think this looks good, you should check out the "Earth's Children" series of books by Jean Auel, also about prehistoric people.  I'm surprised no one has mentioned it here, this movie looks similar.  The first book, "the Clan of the Cave Bear" is an entertaining and truly original book which was made into a HORRIBLE movie in the 1980s (or 1990s?).  I hope this movie does a better job!  Those modern-looking bison (in Europe?) worry me.  Also, why do people slam it because the characters speak English?  What do you expect?  Of course no one spoke English back then (DUH), but would you go see a movie if you couldn't understand the dialog?  If I saw a picture about the life of Jesus I would not expect the actors to speak Aramaic.  Should we slam Shakespeare because he had Julius Caesar speaking English?  No one is going to make a movie that the audience can't understand.  By that logic, Hollywood could never make a movie set in a non-English speaking setting.

text: Ergenekon is a legend about the destruction and rebuilding of the Gokturk (Kokturk) Empire and also serves as an origin myth for Turkish tribes and today‚Äôs Turkic states. The legend takes its name from the Central Asian valley in which fleeing Gokturks sought refuge and a new homeland. Their empire had been destroyed as a result of battles with Chinese and other non-Turkic forces. They fled into a forbidding mountainous region and at its center came across an enormous fruitful valley. They decided to remain there and, melting down all of their iron tools and weapons, created an enormous iron door to seal the only entrance to the valley. Here they lived in peace and the clans flourished and became powerful again. After many generations, they became so numerous that the valley became overpopulated. They decided to melt down the iron door to forge weapons.  However, no one remained of the generation that had led them through the passes, valleys and ravines into the valley, so they wandered aimlessly through the mountains until a gray mother wolf (the symbol on the Gokturk coat of arms) appeared and led them out of the mountains. On the steppes, after many battles, the Gokturk won back their importance, although they never regained their old unity and rather split into many tribes that nevertheless traced their communal origins back to the Gokturk.
author: God of F.

text: Sons of the Grey Wolf: The Turks and the Mongols of old were enemies; but they both claimed to be descended from wolves. One young Turkish warrior, who alone survived after a Mongol raid, was rescued by a she-wolf and led by her to a secret earthly paradise in the mountains. They were married, and their children were led by a great grey wolf to the land which is now Turkey. The Mongol emperor Genghis Khan also claimed to be the son of a wolf.

text: To all the people saying "It's set in Europe, of course the actors are white!" It's set in Europe 20,000 years ago, about 12,000 years BEFORE the development of white skin. The filmmakers were obviously aware of this, as the lead actor - Kodi Smit-McPhee - is a blue-eyed white Australian, and they've given him contacts and tanned skin. Personally, I'm still going to see the film, as it looks amazing and Smit-McPhee is a talented actor. But, while I appreciate the depiction of this early human as non-white, it's still disappointing that Hollywood would rather dress someone up in brown-face than hire a minority actor.

text: Anyone remember the movie Enemy Mine? This is a ripoff of that movie. The story goes, in the far future, humans are at war with an alien Race. Whilst in battle with an enemy spaceship a human crashes on an unknown and dangerous planet, but not before he shot down his alien assailant's ship. They must now form a relationship to survive the hostile planet if they ever wish to see home again. Someone in the comments said something about this being similar to 'How to Train Your Dragon'. In that story, the human chose to help the dragon, but it is different because he lived safely in his village, and put aside honor while choosing compassion. In this video as with Enemy Mine, the protagonist won't survive unless they form this bond with the opposition.

text: Ugh the ignorance on this thread is so annoying. It‚Äôs debated when anatomically modern humans migrated out of Africa but when they did they found they weren‚Äôt the first people to do so. 500,000 ya I think various species of the genus homo, mostly Homo erectus, I think, followed migration paths north and into Europe. Then these people evolved separate of those who stayed in Africa. These people evolved bigger and lighter skinned. These people fought harder for survival and had less free time and developed fewer traits unnecessary for survival such as art, music, and personal expression like their contemporaries in Africa. These people were called the Neanderthals. The lived in Europe when the first anatomically modern humans arrived. These two separate people lived side by side for thousands of years until eventually the Neanderthals died out due to low birth rates and mostly interbreeding with humans, 40,000 ya. Most every European has a good amount of Neanderthal dna in them. Their skin at this time would be lighter. Humans breed very fast compared to Neanderthals. There were relatively few of them compared to Homo sapiens. 20,000 years later is enough time for the Neanderthals dna to become muted and washed out. But it would have left relatively surface changes such as skin color.   There‚Äôs some ancient anthropology 101

In fact that thing looked like a Smilodon. Well, it would if did not have that¬†long tail like a cave lion, which was the only cat back then anything close to that size in Europe and Western Asia. That thing looks like some sort of hybrid between cave lion and Smilodon, which is genetically impossible.

text: *Long rant followed by minor criticism.* The most commonly accepted theory for how wolves and humans first got together is both of them were wandering hunters, and when one area ran out of prey they moved on to another area and because they both were top predators who hunted things till extinction they essentially began following one another. The both of us got used to one another and it wouldn't have been long before we socialised with one another, and from that they became our pets.  I don't really mind the people behind the film wanting to take liberties with how it happened, but considering the truth (no one actually knows) I  think they could have gone down a different route than ripping off How To Train Your Dragon for how the first pairing between man and dog came to.

text: Being both a serious dog lover and a serious wolf lover I must say that I cannot wait to see this movie. I have heard people ask did dogs train human beings or did human beings train dogs. I believe that human beings and dogs trained each other. Dogs helped train man by helping them develop the senses and skills to sense, recognize, and combat dangers in the world as well as hunt for food and humanity trained dogs how to be a companion where they could work together and help each other. Dogs helped the human beings protect their safety and food and in return the human beings shared the food with them, gave them warmth of fire, and protection from enemies that dogs could not handle by using their weapons and providing strength in numbers. This is why the partnership between humanity and dogs has lasted for so long because both sides know they need each other. This is also why dogs are submissive to their human being masters and respect them as the masters and leaders because they know human beings have the power to enforce their will with their advanced brains, minds, and tools that dogs know they do not have or are unable to use. They know human beings can use tools and get what they want so it is better to submit to them and work with them rather than resist and get hurt and possibly even killed and then be forced to obey anyway. I have also heard from the comments of other users who ends of being the true Alpha in the movie: Keda, the character of Kodi Smit-McPhee, or the Chuck the Wolfdog. Yes the Wolfdog who plays in the movie has been named. I believe that it will turn out that they end up working together as a team where both consider the other an equal and neither is the Alpha. But if I had to pick one or the other I would say Keda since human beings have the brains, minds, and tools that make them the dominate species on the planet. I believe that all animals like wolves can sense that human beings are dominate over them in terms of power and that would make Chuck in the movie willing to submit to Keda as leader. That is the process of domestication. Wild animals do not submit to us but domesticated animals who have bonded with us do. Part of bonded with us is that they accept us as the masters and those who are the masters are also the leaders, at least usually. Finally many users have commented that Chuck will probably die before the end of the movie. Although that is definitely possible I think there could be another solution. I believe that Chuck finds a mate and breeds with her, then their puppies become the first little adopted by humanity that starts the selective breeding process leading to the creation of the dog. I guess we will all find out one way or the other by actually watching the movie. To all of you who plan to watch the movie I hope that you greatly enjoy it as much as I do and for those of you who plan not to watch it I can and will respect that. I just ask that you please respect me for choosing to watch it in return.

text: It's a great movie but we domesticated dogs 40,000 years ago in the ice age, not in 20,000. And we don't know what dogs looked like 40,000 years ago. They share some DNA with the grey wolf but may have descended from an unknown, extinct species rather than the grey wolf. Even with DNA it's difficult for scientists to trace back 40,000 years and know what happened back then. But we do know at some point ancient dogs were domesticated and likely were wild animals similar to wolves, just different from wolves. Sort of like how Neanderthals are different from H. Sapiens or Denisovans.

text: Alpha is incredibly spectacular in term of the visual effect. It's so surreal to explore the primitive life of tribes in Stone Age and more surprisingly all the casts speak in native tongue instead of english. It has added some degrees of authenticity in it.  This is first time i have seen the white male leadcast (Kodi Mcphee) in tanned skin color. Tbh, Kodi looks perfect as it the skin color effect creates more exotic vibes which fits Keda, the son of the leader in his tribe.  Typically i have seen lots of movie boy/dog but boy/wolf is entirely new. And i can assure you Alpha aint any common typical pet movie you have ever seen. It's about a chronicle  of young man, Keda who forms an unlikely alliance with a savage wolf and how the two different species alliance slowly evolving as the plot thickens.  A truest masterpiece with originality and 4.5/5 stars flick not to be missed.

text: This was a really good movie and seemed well research. My only complaints are that the language seems to bounce on consistency (if it was a fake language, then there's something about some phonetics and translations that aren't adding up) and that sometimes Keda and the wolf instinctively act like pets and owner. Studies show that our brains changed as we domesticared wolves, so I feel like Keda sometimes does things to Alpha that we do to animals instinctively that might be a result of evolving with wolves. What I'm saying is that Keda acts too much like a modern human, and sometimes Alpha is a bit too doggo.
